# Engineering standards (this repo)

## Terraform & HCL

- Run **`terraform fmt`** on touched `.tf` / `.hcl`; keep `versions.tf` constraints accurate when changing providers or Terraform features.
- Prefer **variables** with descriptions and sensible defaults in `variables.tf`; wire through to resources instead of magic literals.
- Use **`outputs.tf`** for anything operators need (IPs, commands, role ARNs); mark sensitive outputs correctly.
- **Default tags** live in `providers.tf` — extend there instead of one‑off tag blocks unless a resource truly needs an exception.

## Describe how to build, not product specs

- Rules should encode **patterns** (validation, naming, safety), not one‑off UI/feature wishlists.

## What **not** to do

- Do not add heavy SDKs, random CLIs, or alternate IaC tools **unless** the user explicitly asks.
- Do not weaken SSH / SG / IAM trust without calling it out as a **conscious, documented** change.
- Do not reference vague “existing patterns” — point at a real file (e.g. `main.tf` for EC2 wiring, `github_actions_ci.tf` for OIDC trust).

## Documentation freshness (Context7 MCP)

When work touches a **named** framework, library, SDK, **AWS/Terraform provider API**, or CLI whose exact syntax or defaults matter, use the **Context7** MCP: read tool schemas first, **`resolve-library-id`** then **`query-docs`**, unless the user supplied a `/org/project` library id. Prefer Context7 over guessing or stale training data for those lookups. Skip Context7 for pure refactors or generic programming theory with no external API surface.
